</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Computed tomographic (CT) angiography has become the standard of care, supplanting invasive angiography for comprehensive initial evaluation of acute and chronic conditions affecting the vascular system in the abdomen and elsewhere. Over the past decade, the capabilities of CT have improved substantially; simultaneously, the expectations of the referring physician and vascular surgeons have also evolved. Increasingly, CT angiography is used as an imaging biomarker for treatment selection and assessment of effectiveness. However, the growing use of CT angiography has also introduced some challenges, as potential radiation-associated and contrast media–induced risks need to be addressed. These concerns can be partly confronted by modifying scanning parameters (applying a low tube voltage) with or without using software-based solutions. Most recently, multienergy technology has endowed CT with new capabilities offering improved CT angiographic image quality and novel plaque characterization while decreasing radiation and iodine dose. In this article, we discuss current and new approaches using both conventional and multienergy CT for studying vascular disease in the abdomen. We propose various approaches to overcoming commonly encountered image quality challenges in CT angiography. In addition, we describe supplemental strategies for improving patient safety that leverage the available technology.</div><div role="paragraph">©RSNA, 2014</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.345130070">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.345130070">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig1a.jpeg" height="564" width="719" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Axial CT angiographic images obtained with ssDECT <b>(a–d)</b> and dsDECT <b>(e–g)</b> in two patients after endovascular aortic repair (EVAR) who were followed up for endoleak assessment. <b>(a)</b> Conventional SECT image obtained at 140 kVp during the arterial phase shows a type II endoleak (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Iodine <b>(b)</b> and water <b>(c)</b> MD images generated from the arterial phase. Arrow in <b>b</b> = type II endoleak. <b>(d)</b> VM image (65 keV) derived from the delayed phase. Note that the endoleak can be confidently detected in the delayed phase on a low-keV image. <b>(e–g)</b> dsDECT images obtained at 140 kVp <b>(e)</b>, 100 kVp <b>(f)</b>, and 120 kVp (fusion image) <b>(g)</b> during the arterial phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig1b.jpeg" height="564" width="756" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Axial CT angiographic images obtained with ssDECT <b>(a–d)</b> and dsDECT <b>(e–g)</b> in two patients after endovascular aortic repair (EVAR) who were followed up for endoleak assessment. <b>(a)</b> Conventional SECT image obtained at 140 kVp during the arterial phase shows a type II endoleak (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Iodine <b>(b)</b> and water <b>(c)</b> MD images generated from the arterial phase. Arrow in <b>b</b> = type II endoleak. <b>(d)</b> VM image (65 keV) derived from the delayed phase. Note that the endoleak can be confidently detected in the delayed phase on a low-keV image. <b>(e–g)</b> dsDECT images obtained at 140 kVp <b>(e)</b>, 100 kVp <b>(f)</b>, and 120 kVp (fusion image) <b>(g)</b> during the arterial phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig1c.jpeg" height="629" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span> Axial CT angiographic images obtained with ssDECT <b>(a–d)</b> and dsDECT <b>(e–g)</b> in two patients after endovascular aortic repair (EVAR) who were followed up for endoleak assessment. <b>(a)</b> Conventional SECT image obtained at 140 kVp during the arterial phase shows a type II endoleak (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Iodine <b>(b)</b> and water <b>(c)</b> MD images generated from the arterial phase. Arrow in <b>b</b> = type II endoleak. <b>(d)</b> VM image (65 keV) derived from the delayed phase. Note that the endoleak can be confidently detected in the delayed phase on a low-keV image. <b>(e–g)</b> dsDECT images obtained at 140 kVp <b>(e)</b>, 100 kVp <b>(f)</b>, and 120 kVp (fusion image) <b>(g)</b> during the arterial phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig1d.jpeg" height="629" width="683" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span> Axial CT angiographic images obtained with ssDECT <b>(a–d)</b> and dsDECT <b>(e–g)</b> in two patients after endovascular aortic repair (EVAR) who were followed up for endoleak assessment. <b>(a)</b> Conventional SECT image obtained at 140 kVp during the arterial phase shows a type II endoleak (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Iodine <b>(b)</b> and water <b>(c)</b> MD images generated from the arterial phase. Arrow in <b>b</b> = type II endoleak. <b>(d)</b> VM image (65 keV) derived from the delayed phase. Note that the endoleak can be confidently detected in the delayed phase on a low-keV image. <b>(e–g)</b> dsDECT images obtained at 140 kVp <b>(e)</b>, 100 kVp <b>(f)</b>, and 120 kVp (fusion image) <b>(g)</b> during the arterial phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig1e.jpeg" height="735" width="733" aria-labelledby="fig1e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1e</span> Axial CT angiographic images obtained with ssDECT <b>(a–d)</b> and dsDECT <b>(e–g)</b> in two patients after endovascular aortic repair (EVAR) who were followed up for endoleak assessment. <b>(a)</b> Conventional SECT image obtained at 140 kVp during the arterial phase shows a type II endoleak (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Iodine <b>(b)</b> and water <b>(c)</b> MD images generated from the arterial phase. Arrow in <b>b</b> = type II endoleak. <b>(d)</b> VM image (65 keV) derived from the delayed phase. Note that the endoleak can be confidently detected in the delayed phase on a low-keV image. <b>(e–g)</b> dsDECT images obtained at 140 kVp <b>(e)</b>, 100 kVp <b>(f)</b>, and 120 kVp (fusion image) <b>(g)</b> during the arterial phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig1e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig1f.jpeg" height="737" width="741" aria-labelledby="fig1f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1f</span> Axial CT angiographic images obtained with ssDECT <b>(a–d)</b> and dsDECT <b>(e–g)</b> in two patients after endovascular aortic repair (EVAR) who were followed up for endoleak assessment. <b>(a)</b> Conventional SECT image obtained at 140 kVp during the arterial phase shows a type II endoleak (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Iodine <b>(b)</b> and water <b>(c)</b> MD images generated from the arterial phase. Arrow in <b>b</b> = type II endoleak. <b>(d)</b> VM image (65 keV) derived from the delayed phase. Note that the endoleak can be confidently detected in the delayed phase on a low-keV image. <b>(e–g)</b> dsDECT images obtained at 140 kVp <b>(e)</b>, 100 kVp <b>(f)</b>, and 120 kVp (fusion image) <b>(g)</b> during the arterial phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig1f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1g" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig1g.jpeg" height="610" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig1g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1g</span> Axial CT angiographic images obtained with ssDECT <b>(a–d)</b> and dsDECT <b>(e–g)</b> in two patients after endovascular aortic repair (EVAR) who were followed up for endoleak assessment. <b>(a)</b> Conventional SECT image obtained at 140 kVp during the arterial phase shows a type II endoleak (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Iodine <b>(b)</b> and water <b>(c)</b> MD images generated from the arterial phase. Arrow in <b>b</b> = type II endoleak. <b>(d)</b> VM image (65 keV) derived from the delayed phase. Note that the endoleak can be confidently detected in the delayed phase on a low-keV image. <b>(e–g)</b> dsDECT images obtained at 140 kVp <b>(e)</b>, 100 kVp <b>(f)</b>, and 120 kVp (fusion image) <b>(g)</b> during the arterial phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig1g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig2a.jpeg" height="666" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal <b>(c, d)</b> CT angiographic images in a 53-year-old man after EVAR. The attenuation of iodine in the abdominal aorta on the 80-kVp images <b>(a, c)</b> (average, 479 HU) is decreased to approximately 52% on the 140-kVp images <b>(b, d)</b> (average, 251 HU).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig2b.jpeg" height="666" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal <b>(c, d)</b> CT angiographic images in a 53-year-old man after EVAR. The attenuation of iodine in the abdominal aorta on the 80-kVp images <b>(a, c)</b> (average, 479 HU) is decreased to approximately 52% on the 140-kVp images <b>(b, d)</b> (average, 251 HU).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig2c.jpeg" height="698" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span> Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal <b>(c, d)</b> CT angiographic images in a 53-year-old man after EVAR. The attenuation of iodine in the abdominal aorta on the 80-kVp images <b>(a, c)</b> (average, 479 HU) is decreased to approximately 52% on the 140-kVp images <b>(b, d)</b> (average, 251 HU).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig2d.jpeg" height="698" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig2d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2d</span> Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal <b>(c, d)</b> CT angiographic images in a 53-year-old man after EVAR. The attenuation of iodine in the abdominal aorta on the 80-kVp images <b>(a, c)</b> (average, 479 HU) is decreased to approximately 52% on the 140-kVp images <b>(b, d)</b> (average, 251 HU).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig2d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig3a.jpeg" height="799" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Axial DECT <b>(a, b)</b> and conventional CT <b>(c)</b> images in a middle-aged patient after EVAR show a type I endoleak (arrowhead). dsDECT images from VM datasets generated at 50 <b>(a)</b> and 70 <b>(b)</b> keV show increased intravascular attenuation at low energies. There is improved detection of the endoleak on the dsDECT images in comparison with the conventional CT image at 120 kVp <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig3b.jpeg" height="789" width="706" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Axial DECT <b>(a, b)</b> and conventional CT <b>(c)</b> images in a middle-aged patient after EVAR show a type I endoleak (arrowhead). dsDECT images from VM datasets generated at 50 <b>(a)</b> and 70 <b>(b)</b> keV show increased intravascular attenuation at low energies. There is improved detection of the endoleak on the dsDECT images in comparison with the conventional CT image at 120 kVp <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig3c.jpeg" height="789" width="618" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Axial DECT <b>(a, b)</b> and conventional CT <b>(c)</b> images in a middle-aged patient after EVAR show a type I endoleak (arrowhead). dsDECT images from VM datasets generated at 50 <b>(a)</b> and 70 <b>(b)</b> keV show increased intravascular attenuation at low energies. There is improved detection of the endoleak on the dsDECT images in comparison with the conventional CT image at 120 kVp <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig4a.jpeg" height="771" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Partially thrombosed infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) in a middle-aged patient. <b>(a)</b> Axial SECT image obtained during the arterial phase at 120 kVp shows intravascular attenuation of 268 HU. <b>(b, c)</b> Venous phase images obtained with DECT and reconstructed at 70 keV <b>(b)</b> and 50 keV <b>(c)</b> show intravascular attenuation of 135 HU and 285 HU, respectively. Note that similar intravascular attenuation was achieved with the low-keV venous phase image <b>(c)</b> as with the SECT image <b>(a)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig4b.jpeg" height="765" width="849" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Partially thrombosed infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) in a middle-aged patient. <b>(a)</b> Axial SECT image obtained during the arterial phase at 120 kVp shows intravascular attenuation of 268 HU. <b>(b, c)</b> Venous phase images obtained with DECT and reconstructed at 70 keV <b>(b)</b> and 50 keV <b>(c)</b> show intravascular attenuation of 135 HU and 285 HU, respectively. Note that similar intravascular attenuation was achieved with the low-keV venous phase image <b>(c)</b> as with the SECT image <b>(a)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig4c.jpeg" height="765" width="923" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span> Partially thrombosed infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) in a middle-aged patient. <b>(a)</b> Axial SECT image obtained during the arterial phase at 120 kVp shows intravascular attenuation of 268 HU. <b>(b, c)</b> Venous phase images obtained with DECT and reconstructed at 70 keV <b>(b)</b> and 50 keV <b>(c)</b> show intravascular attenuation of 135 HU and 285 HU, respectively. Note that similar intravascular attenuation was achieved with the low-keV venous phase image <b>(c)</b> as with the SECT image <b>(a)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig5a.jpeg" height="1158" width="593" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Infrarenal AAA in a 79-year-old patient. Curved planar reformation <b>(a)</b>, MIP <b>(b)</b>, and 3D volume-rendered <b>(c)</b> images show an infrarenal AAA (arrow) with saccular morphology. Note that the MIP image <b>(b)</b> displays the abdominal aorta along with vascular calcifications, which may interfere with adequate assessment of intraluminal caliber.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig5b.jpeg" height="1158" width="587" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Infrarenal AAA in a 79-year-old patient. Curved planar reformation <b>(a)</b>, MIP <b>(b)</b>, and 3D volume-rendered <b>(c)</b> images show an infrarenal AAA (arrow) with saccular morphology. Note that the MIP image <b>(b)</b> displays the abdominal aorta along with vascular calcifications, which may interfere with adequate assessment of intraluminal caliber.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig5c.jpeg" height="1158" width="669" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> Infrarenal AAA in a 79-year-old patient. Curved planar reformation <b>(a)</b>, MIP <b>(b)</b>, and 3D volume-rendered <b>(c)</b> images show an infrarenal AAA (arrow) with saccular morphology. Note that the MIP image <b>(b)</b> displays the abdominal aorta along with vascular calcifications, which may interfere with adequate assessment of intraluminal caliber.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig6a.jpeg" height="1400" width="667" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Pseudoaneurysm of the thoracic aorta in a 64-year-old patient. MIP images from thoracoabdominal CT angiography without <b>(a)</b> and with <b>(b)</b> bone and plaque subtraction show the pseudoaneurysm. Calcified plaques and bone can be discriminated from intraluminal contrast medium (iodine) based on attenuation differences at high and low x-ray energies. Note that heavily calcified arteries on the unsubtracted image <b>(a)</b> have been removed on the calcium-subtracted image <b>(b)</b>. Therefore, use of plaque and bone subtraction may lead to overestimation of vessel stenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig6b.jpeg" height="1400" width="658" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Pseudoaneurysm of the thoracic aorta in a 64-year-old patient. MIP images from thoracoabdominal CT angiography without <b>(a)</b> and with <b>(b)</b> bone and plaque subtraction show the pseudoaneurysm. Calcified plaques and bone can be discriminated from intraluminal contrast medium (iodine) based on attenuation differences at high and low x-ray energies. Note that heavily calcified arteries on the unsubtracted image <b>(a)</b> have been removed on the calcium-subtracted image <b>(b)</b>. Therefore, use of plaque and bone subtraction may lead to overestimation of vessel stenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig7a.jpeg" height="1479" width="656" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Automated vessel analysis of an infrarenal AAA in a 58-year-old patient. Automated vessel analysis software enables generation of a curved planar reformation image <b>(a)</b>, 3D volume-rendered image with a centerline for vessel tracking <b>(b)</b>, stretch vessel display image <b>(c)</b>, and axial images with automated vessel diameters at the proximal <b>(d)</b>, middle <b>(e)</b>, and distal <b>(f)</b> segments of the AAA (red lines in <b>c</b>). Automated vessel analysis facilitates measurement of aortic calibers for the proximal, middle, and distal portions of the AAA <b>(d–f)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig7b.jpeg" height="1479" width="630" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Automated vessel analysis of an infrarenal AAA in a 58-year-old patient. Automated vessel analysis software enables generation of a curved planar reformation image <b>(a)</b>, 3D volume-rendered image with a centerline for vessel tracking <b>(b)</b>, stretch vessel display image <b>(c)</b>, and axial images with automated vessel diameters at the proximal <b>(d)</b>, middle <b>(e)</b>, and distal <b>(f)</b> segments of the AAA (red lines in <b>c</b>). Automated vessel analysis facilitates measurement of aortic calibers for the proximal, middle, and distal portions of the AAA <b>(d–f)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig7c.jpeg" height="1479" width="556" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span> Automated vessel analysis of an infrarenal AAA in a 58-year-old patient. Automated vessel analysis software enables generation of a curved planar reformation image <b>(a)</b>, 3D volume-rendered image with a centerline for vessel tracking <b>(b)</b>, stretch vessel display image <b>(c)</b>, and axial images with automated vessel diameters at the proximal <b>(d)</b>, middle <b>(e)</b>, and distal <b>(f)</b> segments of the AAA (red lines in <b>c</b>). Automated vessel analysis facilitates measurement of aortic calibers for the proximal, middle, and distal portions of the AAA <b>(d–f)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig7d.jpeg" height="594" width="864" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span> Automated vessel analysis of an infrarenal AAA in a 58-year-old patient. Automated vessel analysis software enables generation of a curved planar reformation image <b>(a)</b>, 3D volume-rendered image with a centerline for vessel tracking <b>(b)</b>, stretch vessel display image <b>(c)</b>, and axial images with automated vessel diameters at the proximal <b>(d)</b>, middle <b>(e)</b>, and distal <b>(f)</b> segments of the AAA (red lines in <b>c</b>). Automated vessel analysis facilitates measurement of aortic calibers for the proximal, middle, and distal portions of the AAA <b>(d–f)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig7e.jpeg" height="594" width="1010" aria-labelledby="fig7e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7e</span> Automated vessel analysis of an infrarenal AAA in a 58-year-old patient. Automated vessel analysis software enables generation of a curved planar reformation image <b>(a)</b>, 3D volume-rendered image with a centerline for vessel tracking <b>(b)</b>, stretch vessel display image <b>(c)</b>, and axial images with automated vessel diameters at the proximal <b>(d)</b>, middle <b>(e)</b>, and distal <b>(f)</b> segments of the AAA (red lines in <b>c</b>). Automated vessel analysis facilitates measurement of aortic calibers for the proximal, middle, and distal portions of the AAA <b>(d–f)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig7e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig7f.jpeg" height="568" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig7f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7f</span> Automated vessel analysis of an infrarenal AAA in a 58-year-old patient. Automated vessel analysis software enables generation of a curved planar reformation image <b>(a)</b>, 3D volume-rendered image with a centerline for vessel tracking <b>(b)</b>, stretch vessel display image <b>(c)</b>, and axial images with automated vessel diameters at the proximal <b>(d)</b>, middle <b>(e)</b>, and distal <b>(f)</b> segments of the AAA (red lines in <b>c</b>). Automated vessel analysis facilitates measurement of aortic calibers for the proximal, middle, and distal portions of the AAA <b>(d–f)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig7f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig8a.jpeg" height="690" width="613" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Virtual angioscopy in a 60-year-old patient after EVAR. <b>(a)</b> Stretch vessel display image. <b>(b–d)</b> Virtual angioscopic images of the proximal <b>(b)</b>, middle <b>(c)</b>, and distal <b>(d)</b> portions of the endostent (red lines in <b>a</b>). Virtual angioscopy enables the user to assess the integrity of the stent as well as evaluate for adequate attachment of the stent to the vessel walls.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig8b.jpeg" height="690" width="861" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Virtual angioscopy in a 60-year-old patient after EVAR. <b>(a)</b> Stretch vessel display image. <b>(b–d)</b> Virtual angioscopic images of the proximal <b>(b)</b>, middle <b>(c)</b>, and distal <b>(d)</b> portions of the endostent (red lines in <b>a</b>). Virtual angioscopy enables the user to assess the integrity of the stent as well as evaluate for adequate attachment of the stent to the vessel walls.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig8c.jpeg" height="679" width="764" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span> Virtual angioscopy in a 60-year-old patient after EVAR. <b>(a)</b> Stretch vessel display image. <b>(b–d)</b> Virtual angioscopic images of the proximal <b>(b)</b>, middle <b>(c)</b>, and distal <b>(d)</b> portions of the endostent (red lines in <b>a</b>). Virtual angioscopy enables the user to assess the integrity of the stent as well as evaluate for adequate attachment of the stent to the vessel walls.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig8d.jpeg" height="679" width="711" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span> Virtual angioscopy in a 60-year-old patient after EVAR. <b>(a)</b> Stretch vessel display image. <b>(b–d)</b> Virtual angioscopic images of the proximal <b>(b)</b>, middle <b>(c)</b>, and distal <b>(d)</b> portions of the endostent (red lines in <b>a</b>). Virtual angioscopy enables the user to assess the integrity of the stent as well as evaluate for adequate attachment of the stent to the vessel walls.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig9a.jpeg" height="651" width="742" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Evaluation of stent patency in a 65-year-old woman after EVAR. Axial 120-kV SECT image <b>(a)</b> and 140-keV VM image from DECT <b>(b)</b> show the stent. Note that the 140-keV image <b>(b)</b> enables evaluation of stent patency by reducing beam-hardening artifacts (arrow) in comparison with the 120-kV SECT image <b>(a)</b>. The stent is patent.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig9b.jpeg" height="651" width="732" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Evaluation of stent patency in a 65-year-old woman after EVAR. Axial 120-kV SECT image <b>(a)</b> and 140-keV VM image from DECT <b>(b)</b> show the stent. Note that the 140-keV image <b>(b)</b> enables evaluation of stent patency by reducing beam-hardening artifacts (arrow) in comparison with the 120-kV SECT image <b>(a)</b>. The stent is patent.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig10a.jpeg" height="553" width="920" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> CT angiography in two patients with atherosclerotic disease. MD images from dsDECT <b>(a, b)</b> and ssDECT <b>(c–e)</b> show calcified plaques (arrow) in the right and left iliac arteries. The plaque display images (<b>a, c</b> and <b>d, e</b>) can be created by combination of the calcium and iodine image pair, respectively. Note that accurate assessment of vessel stenosis is achieved when the plaque display is used <b>(a)</b>, as it reduces blooming artifact in comparison with conventional CT <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig10b.jpeg" height="553" width="956" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> CT angiography in two patients with atherosclerotic disease. MD images from dsDECT <b>(a, b)</b> and ssDECT <b>(c–e)</b> show calcified plaques (arrow) in the right and left iliac arteries. The plaque display images (<b>a, c</b> and <b>d, e</b>) can be created by combination of the calcium and iodine image pair, respectively. Note that accurate assessment of vessel stenosis is achieved when the plaque display is used <b>(a)</b>, as it reduces blooming artifact in comparison with conventional CT <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig10c.jpeg" height="1134" width="1074" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> CT angiography in two patients with atherosclerotic disease. MD images from dsDECT <b>(a, b)</b> and ssDECT <b>(c–e)</b> show calcified plaques (arrow) in the right and left iliac arteries. The plaque display images (<b>a, c</b> and <b>d, e</b>) can be created by combination of the calcium and iodine image pair, respectively. Note that accurate assessment of vessel stenosis is achieved when the plaque display is used <b>(a)</b>, as it reduces blooming artifact in comparison with conventional CT <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig10d.jpeg" height="548" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span> CT angiography in two patients with atherosclerotic disease. MD images from dsDECT <b>(a, b)</b> and ssDECT <b>(c–e)</b> show calcified plaques (arrow) in the right and left iliac arteries. The plaque display images (<b>a, c</b> and <b>d, e</b>) can be created by combination of the calcium and iodine image pair, respectively. Note that accurate assessment of vessel stenosis is achieved when the plaque display is used <b>(a)</b>, as it reduces blooming artifact in comparison with conventional CT <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig10e.jpeg" height="511" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig10e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10e</span> CT angiography in two patients with atherosclerotic disease. MD images from dsDECT <b>(a, b)</b> and ssDECT <b>(c–e)</b> show calcified plaques (arrow) in the right and left iliac arteries. The plaque display images (<b>a, c</b> and <b>d, e</b>) can be created by combination of the calcium and iodine image pair, respectively. Note that accurate assessment of vessel stenosis is achieved when the plaque display is used <b>(a)</b>, as it reduces blooming artifact in comparison with conventional CT <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig10e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig11a.jpeg" height="587" width="782" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Plaque characterization with SECT in a 51-year-old patient with atherosclerotic disease. <b>(a–c)</b> Conventional CT angiographic images show plaque in the superior mesenteric artery <b>(a, b)</b> and abdominal aorta <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d–f)</b> Corresponding SECT images allow plaque characterization by displaying different components such as fat (yellow-brown), soft tissue (yellow-brown), and calcium (red). Green = vessel lumen with intraluminal contrast medium. The color-coding was generated using the advanced vessel analysis software tools available on the workstation (ADW 4.5, GE Healthcare), which enable application of user-predefined attenuation thresholds. The proportion of these components seems to predict the risk of thrombosis or embolization. The presence of ulcerative plaques in the abdominal aorta <b>(c, f)</b> puts the patient at risk for distal embolism.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig11b.jpeg" height="587" width="691" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Plaque characterization with SECT in a 51-year-old patient with atherosclerotic disease. <b>(a–c)</b> Conventional CT angiographic images show plaque in the superior mesenteric artery <b>(a, b)</b> and abdominal aorta <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d–f)</b> Corresponding SECT images allow plaque characterization by displaying different components such as fat (yellow-brown), soft tissue (yellow-brown), and calcium (red). Green = vessel lumen with intraluminal contrast medium. The color-coding was generated using the advanced vessel analysis software tools available on the workstation (ADW 4.5, GE Healthcare), which enable application of user-predefined attenuation thresholds. The proportion of these components seems to predict the risk of thrombosis or embolization. The presence of ulcerative plaques in the abdominal aorta <b>(c, f)</b> puts the patient at risk for distal embolism.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig11c.jpeg" height="606" width="875" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span> Plaque characterization with SECT in a 51-year-old patient with atherosclerotic disease. <b>(a–c)</b> Conventional CT angiographic images show plaque in the superior mesenteric artery <b>(a, b)</b> and abdominal aorta <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d–f)</b> Corresponding SECT images allow plaque characterization by displaying different components such as fat (yellow-brown), soft tissue (yellow-brown), and calcium (red). Green = vessel lumen with intraluminal contrast medium. The color-coding was generated using the advanced vessel analysis software tools available on the workstation (ADW 4.5, GE Healthcare), which enable application of user-predefined attenuation thresholds. The proportion of these components seems to predict the risk of thrombosis or embolization. The presence of ulcerative plaques in the abdominal aorta <b>(c, f)</b> puts the patient at risk for distal embolism.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig11d.jpeg" height="606" width="600" aria-labelledby="fig11d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span> Plaque characterization with SECT in a 51-year-old patient with atherosclerotic disease. <b>(a–c)</b> Conventional CT angiographic images show plaque in the superior mesenteric artery <b>(a, b)</b> and abdominal aorta <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d–f)</b> Corresponding SECT images allow plaque characterization by displaying different components such as fat (yellow-brown), soft tissue (yellow-brown), and calcium (red). Green = vessel lumen with intraluminal contrast medium. The color-coding was generated using the advanced vessel analysis software tools available on the workstation (ADW 4.5, GE Healthcare), which enable application of user-predefined attenuation thresholds. The proportion of these components seems to predict the risk of thrombosis or embolization. The presence of ulcerative plaques in the abdominal aorta <b>(c, f)</b> puts the patient at risk for distal embolism.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig11e.jpeg" height="592" width="688" aria-labelledby="fig11e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11e</span> Plaque characterization with SECT in a 51-year-old patient with atherosclerotic disease. <b>(a–c)</b> Conventional CT angiographic images show plaque in the superior mesenteric artery <b>(a, b)</b> and abdominal aorta <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d–f)</b> Corresponding SECT images allow plaque characterization by displaying different components such as fat (yellow-brown), soft tissue (yellow-brown), and calcium (red). Green = vessel lumen with intraluminal contrast medium. The color-coding was generated using the advanced vessel analysis software tools available on the workstation (ADW 4.5, GE Healthcare), which enable application of user-predefined attenuation thresholds. The proportion of these components seems to predict the risk of thrombosis or embolization. The presence of ulcerative plaques in the abdominal aorta <b>(c, f)</b> puts the patient at risk for distal embolism.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig11e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig11f.jpeg" height="592" width="679" aria-labelledby="fig11f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11f</span> Plaque characterization with SECT in a 51-year-old patient with atherosclerotic disease. <b>(a–c)</b> Conventional CT angiographic images show plaque in the superior mesenteric artery <b>(a, b)</b> and abdominal aorta <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d–f)</b> Corresponding SECT images allow plaque characterization by displaying different components such as fat (yellow-brown), soft tissue (yellow-brown), and calcium (red). Green = vessel lumen with intraluminal contrast medium. The color-coding was generated using the advanced vessel analysis software tools available on the workstation (ADW 4.5, GE Healthcare), which enable application of user-predefined attenuation thresholds. The proportion of these components seems to predict the risk of thrombosis or embolization. The presence of ulcerative plaques in the abdominal aorta <b>(c, f)</b> puts the patient at risk for distal embolism.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig11f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig12a.jpeg" height="649" width="762" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> DECT angiography in two patients followed up for endoleak assessment after EVAR. Axial images were obtained with ssDECT <b>(a–c)</b> and dsDECT <b>(d–f)</b>. Note that the MD water image <b>(a)</b> is comparable to the true noncontrast image <b>(b)</b> and shows similar attenuation of the aneurysmal sac. Similarly, the virtual unenhanced image <b>(d)</b> is comparable to the true noncontrast image <b>(e)</b>. Both series (<b>a</b> and <b>d</b>) can replace true noncontrast images and can aid in diagnosis of endoleak (arrow in <b>c</b> and <b>f</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig12b.jpeg" height="649" width="712" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> DECT angiography in two patients followed up for endoleak assessment after EVAR. Axial images were obtained with ssDECT <b>(a–c)</b> and dsDECT <b>(d–f)</b>. Note that the MD water image <b>(a)</b> is comparable to the true noncontrast image <b>(b)</b> and shows similar attenuation of the aneurysmal sac. Similarly, the virtual unenhanced image <b>(d)</b> is comparable to the true noncontrast image <b>(e)</b>. Both series (<b>a</b> and <b>d</b>) can replace true noncontrast images and can aid in diagnosis of endoleak (arrow in <b>c</b> and <b>f</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig12c.jpeg" height="635" width="768" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> DECT angiography in two patients followed up for endoleak assessment after EVAR. Axial images were obtained with ssDECT <b>(a–c)</b> and dsDECT <b>(d–f)</b>. Note that the MD water image <b>(a)</b> is comparable to the true noncontrast image <b>(b)</b> and shows similar attenuation of the aneurysmal sac. Similarly, the virtual unenhanced image <b>(d)</b> is comparable to the true noncontrast image <b>(e)</b>. Both series (<b>a</b> and <b>d</b>) can replace true noncontrast images and can aid in diagnosis of endoleak (arrow in <b>c</b> and <b>f</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig12d.jpeg" height="635" width="706" aria-labelledby="fig12d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span> DECT angiography in two patients followed up for endoleak assessment after EVAR. Axial images were obtained with ssDECT <b>(a–c)</b> and dsDECT <b>(d–f)</b>. Note that the MD water image <b>(a)</b> is comparable to the true noncontrast image <b>(b)</b> and shows similar attenuation of the aneurysmal sac. Similarly, the virtual unenhanced image <b>(d)</b> is comparable to the true noncontrast image <b>(e)</b>. Both series (<b>a</b> and <b>d</b>) can replace true noncontrast images and can aid in diagnosis of endoleak (arrow in <b>c</b> and <b>f</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig12e.jpeg" height="599" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig12e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12e</span> DECT angiography in two patients followed up for endoleak assessment after EVAR. Axial images were obtained with ssDECT <b>(a–c)</b> and dsDECT <b>(d–f)</b>. Note that the MD water image <b>(a)</b> is comparable to the true noncontrast image <b>(b)</b> and shows similar attenuation of the aneurysmal sac. Similarly, the virtual unenhanced image <b>(d)</b> is comparable to the true noncontrast image <b>(e)</b>. Both series (<b>a</b> and <b>d</b>) can replace true noncontrast images and can aid in diagnosis of endoleak (arrow in <b>c</b> and <b>f</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig12e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig12f.jpeg" height="599" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig12f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12f</span> DECT angiography in two patients followed up for endoleak assessment after EVAR. Axial images were obtained with ssDECT <b>(a–c)</b> and dsDECT <b>(d–f)</b>. Note that the MD water image <b>(a)</b> is comparable to the true noncontrast image <b>(b)</b> and shows similar attenuation of the aneurysmal sac. Similarly, the virtual unenhanced image <b>(d)</b> is comparable to the true noncontrast image <b>(e)</b>. Both series (<b>a</b> and <b>d</b>) can replace true noncontrast images and can aid in diagnosis of endoleak (arrow in <b>c</b> and <b>f</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig12f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130070/asset/images/large/rg.345130070.fig13.jpeg" height="713" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span> CT angiography performed with low-dose contrast medium (45 mL) in a 58-year-old patient with impaired renal and cardiac function. A high concentration of contrast medium (370 mg/mL) was used with a saline flush, combined with an acquisition of 100 kVp to increase iodine attenuation. The study has acceptable image quality and is able to demonstrate a type II endoleak (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130070&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Boone JM. Multidetector CT: opportunities, challenges, and concerns associated with scanners with 64 or more detector rows. <em>Radiology</em> 2006;241(2): 334–337.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/radiol.2412060169">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17057062/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Multidetector+CT%3A+opportunities%2C+challenges%2C+and+concerns+associated+with+scanners+with+64+or+more+detector+rows&amp;author=JM+Boone&amp;publication_year=2006&amp;journal=Radiology&amp;pages=334-337&amp;doi=10.1148%2Fradiol.2412060169&amp;pmid=17057062">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Yikilmaz A, Karahan OI, Senol S, Tuna IS, Akyildiz HY. Value of multislice computed tomography in the diagnosis of acute mesenteric ischemia. <em>Eur J Radiol</em> 2011;80(2):297–302.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/1